snippet.textDisplay:
In the U.S., 80,000 people died of flu, winter 2017; population of 329 million = .ooo2% of population...that's approximately 889 deaths every day, for 3 months.
Wuhan Coronavirus officially presented on 8th of December 2019 and, ONLY 800 deaths??? In a population of 1.4 BILLION (1 thousand, 400 million), that = .000003% of the population...at a rate of ONLY 6-7 deaths, per day.


Coronaviruses (7 strains) were discovered in the 1960s, and no vaccine has been successfully developed.
Novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV), also known as Wuhan coronavirus.- 800+ confirmed deaths, in 2 months.

Preliminary study providing a tentative 3% estimate for case fatality rate.
Mortality rate for SARS was 10% and for MERS 34% ...case-fatality proportion in this cohort is approximately 14.6%, and the overall case fatality proportion appears to be closer to 3%.

Importantly, in emerging viral infection outbreaks the case-fatality ratio is often OVERESTIMATED in the early stages because case detection is highly biased towards the more severe cases.
As further data on the spectrum of mild or asymptomatic infection becomes available, the case-fatality ratio is likely to DECREASE.
